t%3B%20Foust%20said%20in%20a%20National%20Museum%20of%20the%20US%20Air%20Force%20video%20in%20October%202013%2C%20%26quot%3Bit%20did%20not%20recover.%26quot%3B%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%20data-embed-type%3D%5C%22youtube%5C%22%20data-type%3D%5C%22embed%5C%22%3E%20%3Ciframe%20width%3D%5C%22560%5C%22%20allowfullscreen%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.youtube.com%2Fembed%2F3M2XZEYqIpQ%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22315%5C%22%3E%3C%2Fiframe%3E%20%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cp%3EAfter%20Foust%20ejected%2C%20the%20aircraft%20nose-dived%20before%20stabilizing%2C%20then%20remained%20airborne%20for%20a%20time%2C%20while%20Foust%20drifted%20around%208%2C000%20feet%20above%20the%20ground%20in%20his%20parachute.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBut%20instead%20of%20crashing%20and%20leaving%20a%20broken%20plane%20amid%20scattered%20debris%20and%20wreckage%2C%20the%20F-106%20made%20an%20apparently%20graceful%20landing%20in%20a%20snowy%20farmer's%20field%20in%20Montana.%20%26quot%3BIt%20was%20about%20six%20inches%20of%20snow%20on%20the%20ground%2C%26quot%3B%20Foust%20said%2C%20adding%20that%20it%20had%20%26quot%3Bprobably%20skidded%20some%20couple%20hundred%20yards%20or%20more%20and%20came%20to%20rest.%26quot%3B%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EShockingly%2C%20the%20F-106%20suffered%20little%20damage%20during%20its%20belly%20landing%20beyond%20some%20underside%20skinning.%20%26quot%3BI%20was%20surprised%20that%20that%20was%20the%20case%2C%26quot%3B%20Foust%20said.%20%26quot%3BI%20assumed%20it%20crashed%20but%20the%20fact%20that%20it%20landed%20by%20itself%20was%20obviously%20a%20shock%20to%20everyone.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20unusual%20event%20earned%20his%20aircraft%20its%20%26quot%3BCornfield%20Bomber%26quot%3B%20nickname%2C%20and%20shortly%20after%20it%20was%20taken%20to%20McClellan%20Air%20Force%20Base%20for%20repairs%2C%20it%20returned%20to%20service.%20Since%20August%201986%2C%20it%20has%20been%20on%20display%20at%20the%20National%20Museum%20of%20the%20US%20Air%20Force.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%3ERead%20the%20original%2